The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal
 Thursday, May 06, 2004 				 Police thrash lover in lock-up
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Durgapur, May 5: Picked up, but not arrested, Rajesh Gurung, 24, was severely beaten up in a lock-up and kept confined through the night of May 1 without any case registered against him. 																								Gurung was accused of marrying Piyali Sarkar, 19, against the wishes of her family. 																								The torture came to light today after he was released from Durgapur Subdivisional Hospital, where he was admitted on Monday morning. 																								The boy lived close to Piyalis house at DPL Township, about 160 km from Calcutta, and they were going around for some time. 																								We had planned to escape and get married in court. Accordingly, we left our homes on the night of April 27 and stayed at a friends house in Durgapur, Gurung said. The same night, Piyalis father lodged a complaint with the police, alleging that he had abducted his daughter.																								Gurung said an officer took away his marriage certificate when he went to Coke Oven police station with Piyali to say that they were legally married. Piyalis father Harisadhan was at the police station when the beating began.																								Burdwan superintendent of police K.C. Meena said: Ive asked additional superintendent, Durgapur, Sunil Halder to conduct a thorough probe.
